4. What We Never Collect
Our Commitments
These are firm commitments, not aspirations. Stratum is built to make these technically impossible, not just policy-prohibited.

•	We never transmit your source code to Stratum servers. Ever.
•	We never transmit your file names, class names, or project names to Stratum servers.
•	We never transmit your git history, commit messages, or branch names.
•	We never read files outside the workspace folder you have opened in VS Code.
•	We never store the content of your .stratum/access.json (your team role configuration) on our servers.
•	We never sell, rent, or trade your data to third parties for marketing or advertising purposes.
•	We never use your code or project data to train AI models.
•	We never build profiles of individual users or track behaviour across multiple projects.

5. NL Input and Third-Party AI Processing
The NL input feature allows you to describe what you want to build in plain English. Stratum interprets your description and proposes a structured Scenario. This feature uses a third-party AI language model to perform the interpretation.
5.1 Consent Requirement
NL input processing via a third-party AI provider is never enabled by default. The first time you attempt to use the NL input bar, Stratum displays an explicit consent prompt explaining what will be sent and to which provider. You must actively choose to allow this. You can use NL input in 'offline mode' (a local rule-based classifier) at any time without consenting to third-party processing.
5.2 What Is Sent to the AI Provider
•	Your plain-English description text (what you typed in the NL input bar)
•	Structured context about your project: the names of existing Screens, existing Scenarios, and data entity names — provided as a structured list, not as raw file content
•	The Plugin's interpretation task instructions (a system prompt that does not contain any of your code or project content)

5.3 What Is Never Sent to the AI Provider
•	Your source code (no file content, no function bodies, no class definitions)
•	Your actual file names or directory structure
•	The content of your .stratum/ model files
•	Your git identity, email address, or commit history
•	Any data from your .stratum/access.json

5.4 AI Provider Selection
You may configure which AI language model provider processes your NL input in Stratum Settings. The available providers are listed in Stratum's documentation at docs.stratum.dev/nl-providers. Each provider's own privacy policy governs how they handle the data they receive from Stratum.
The current list of supported AI language model providers, together with links to their respective privacy policies, is maintained in Stratum's documentation at docs.stratum.dev/nl-providers and is updated whenever a new provider is added or removed.

Stratum has a Data Processing Agreement (DPA) in place with each supported provider. Under these agreements, input data is not used to train the provider's models, and is subject to the provider's standard data retention and deletion policies.
5.5 Revoking NL Consent
You can withdraw your consent to third-party NL processing at any time by opening Stratum Settings → NL Input → 'Switch to offline mode'. This immediately stops any further API calls to third-party providers. Previously transmitted descriptions cannot be retroactively deleted from the provider's infrastructure; the provider's own retention and deletion policies apply.

6. Automatic Git Commits
When you make changes to Stratum canvases, the Plugin may automatically create git commits in your local repository on your behalf. These commits:
•	Are made to your local repository only — Stratum does not push commits to any remote on your behalf without your explicit instruction.
•	Use your existing git identity (git config user.email and user.name) — Stratum does not set or override your git identity.
•	Include a role tag in the commit message (e.g., [PO: you@company.com]) so your team can see which changes were made via Stratum and in what role capacity.
•	Are visible in your repository's git log and can be reverted at any time using standard git commands.
You can disable auto-commits entirely in Stratum Settings → Sync → 'Manual commits only'. In this mode, Stratum stages changes but does not commit them — you commit them yourself.

7. Telemetry and Analytics
7.1 What We Collect (Opt-In Only)
If you choose to enable anonymous usage statistics (which is always opt-in and never the default), Stratum collects the following aggregate counts:
•	Which canvas panels were opened and approximately how many times
•	Whether the NL input feature was used (count only — not the content)
•	Whether specific error types were encountered (error code only — not your code)
•	Plugin version, VS Code version, and operating system type

7.2 What We Never Collect in Telemetry
•	Any source code content
•	Any NL input text
•	Any file names, class names, or project names
•	Any personal identifiers — your email address is never included in telemetry events
•	Any information that could identify you individually

7.3 How to Enable or Disable
Telemetry is disabled by default. To enable it: Stratum Settings → Privacy → 'Share anonymous usage statistics'. To disable it at any time: the same setting. If VS Code's global telemetry setting is set to 'off', Stratum respects this setting and disables all telemetry regardless of Stratum's individual setting.

8. Crash Reports
When Stratum encounters an unexpected error, it may show a notification: '[Something went wrong in the HRSG panel] — your work is safe. [Send crash report] [Dismiss]'. Crash reports are never sent automatically — you must click 'Send crash report' to transmit one.
8.1 What a Crash Report Contains
•	The error message and stack trace (internal Plugin function names — not your code)
•	The Plugin version, VS Code version, and operating system
•	The name of the canvas panel that was active at the time of the crash
•	A snapshot of the relevant canvas model state — PII-scrubbed before transmission: all entity names, scenario names, and field names are replaced with generic identifiers (e.g., 'entity_1', 'scenario_2')

8.2 What a Crash Report Never Contains
•	Your source code
•	Your actual entity names, scenario names, or field values
•	Your git identity or email address
•	The full content of any file in your workspace

9. Data Sharing and Third Parties
Stratum does not sell, rent, or trade any of your data. We share data only in the following limited circumstances:
•	AI language model providers: only NL input text as described in Section 5, only after your consent, and under Data Processing Agreements.
•	Stripe: billing information for Team and Enterprise customers, under Stripe's standard data processing agreement.
•	Infrastructure providers (AWS, Cloudflare): hosting of the Stratum web properties and, for Team/Enterprise customers, account and project data storage. These providers process data only on our behalf and under data processing agreements.
•	Crash reporting service (Sentry): PII-scrubbed crash reports that you choose to submit, under our DPA with Sentry.
•	Legal requirements: if we are required by law, court order, or regulatory authority to disclose data, we will do so and will notify you unless legally prohibited from doing so.
•	Business transfer: if Stratum is acquired or merged, your data may be transferred to the acquirer under the same privacy protections. We will notify you before any such transfer.

